storyPoints.name: Background: The Expansion of Nazi Germany

slide.text: Before invading the Soviet Union, Nazi Germany had already conquered much of Europe through a series of rapid and aggressive campaigns. These invasions established strategic control and allowed Germany to launch Operation Barbarossa from a broad eastern front.

On June 22, 1941, Nazi Germany launched a massive surprise invasion of the Soviet Union with three major army groups:
North, Center, and South. Each group advanced toward critical Soviet cities along a wide front, aiming to defeat the Red Army in a rapid campaign.

After initial rapid advances, German forces met strong Soviet resistance at Smolensk. Although they captured the city, Soviet counterattacks slowed the German advance, delaying their drive toward Moscow.

German and Finnish forces surrounded Leningrad, beginning a brutal 872-day siege that would become one of the longest and deadliest in history. Despite heavy casualties and starvation, the city never surrendered.

Despite early successes, German forces encountered worsening weather and Soviet resistance as they advanced toward Moscow. The Red Army launched a massive counteroffensive in December, pushing the Germans back.

As winter set in, the Soviets launched a massive counteroffensive, exploiting German weaknesses. The Wehrmacht, unprepared for the extreme cold, was forced into retreat, marking the end of Operation Barbarossa.
